    <h2 id="verbType"> Irregular vs Regular Verbs </h2>
    <p> First things first, French has several different ways of conjugating their verbs.
        If a verb conjugation follows a specific pattern shared by other verbs, it is said to be a <strong><em>regular</em></strong> verb, but if it doesn't follow a pattern,
      or say if it only follows a very small pattern with a handful of other verbs, it is <strong><em>irregular</em></strong>, because it must be memorized alone.
    </p>
    <p> <strong>There are three main kinds of regular verbs:</strong> </p>
    <ul>
      <li> verbs ending in <strong>"-er,"</strong> like <em>parler</em> </li>
      <li> verbs ending in <strong>"-re,"</strong> like <em>vendre</em> </li>
      <li> verbs ending in <strong>"-ir,"</strong> like <em>choisir</em></li>
    </ul>
    <p> Most of the time, when you are conjugating a regular verb, you are changing or replacing the end of the word
      and perhaps adding in a helping verb (like in English, <em> I jump, I <strong>will</strong> jump or I <strong>have</strong> jumped</em>).
      <br><br> Other times, especially in irregular verbs, you are changing the whole word when you conjugate it (also like in English, <em>I am, I was, I will be</em>).
    </p>
    <p> In the sections below, you will see a couple examples of how regular verbs are conjugated in the present tense so you understand how to apply the patterns to other regular verbs.
      The patterns for the other tenses will be given in their respective sections.
    </p>
    <p> <em><strong>Note:</strong> Not all verbs that have these endings are regular verbs. Many are irregular, and will be talked about in the <strong>Irregular Verbs</strong> section.</em>
    </p>

    <h3> Regular ER Verbs </h3>
      <p> All regular ER verbs can be conjugated in the same way. The "<em>-er</em>" gets dropped off of the word and replaced with an ending that reflects who is doing the action.
        English only does this for <em>he, she,</em> or <em>it</em> (like <em>I eat</em> vs <em>he eat<strong>s</strong></em>), but French does this for I, you (singular and plural), he, she, we, and they(male and female).
        The way a verb is conjugated depends on what <em>person</em> it is in.
        <br><br> Here are a couple of examples how regular ER verbs are conjugated in present tense. Notice how the ends of the words have been changed in the same way:
      </p>
      <div class="example">
      <table class="table1">
        <caption>Parler - To speak</caption>
        <tr class="rowHeader">
          <th>Person</th>
          <th>Conjugation</th>
          <th>Person</th>
          <th>Conjugation</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Je</td>
          <td>parl<em><strong>e</strong></em></td>
          <td>Nous</td>
          <td>parl<em><strong>ons</strong></em></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Tu</td>
          <td>parl<em><strong>es</em></strong></td>
          <td>Vous</td>
          <td>parl<em><strong>ez</em></strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Il, elle, on</td>
          <td>parl<em><strong>e</em></strong></td>
          <td>Ils, elles</td>
          <td>parl<em><strong>ent</em></strong></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <table class="table2">
        <caption>Danser - To dance</caption>
        <tr class="rowHeader">
          <th>Person</th>
          <th>Conjugation</th>
          <th>Person</th>
          <th>Conjugation</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Je</td>
          <td>dans<em><strong>e</strong></em></td>
          <td>Nous</td>
          <td>dans<em><strong>ons</strong></em></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Tu</td>
          <td>dans<em><strong>es</em></strong></td>
          <td>Vous</td>
          <td>dans<em><strong>ez</em></strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Il, elle, on</td>
          <td>dans<em><strong>e</em></strong></td>
          <td>Ils, elles</td>
          <td>dans<em><strong>ent</em></strong></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>
      <p> There are some ER verbs that end in "-ger."
        These verbs still follow the same basic pattern, but notice how in the <em>nous</em> form, the ending keeps the "e."
        This reflects pronunciation and is left to show that the "g" is still pronounced like a "j" and not a "g" like in "golf."
      </p>
      <div class="example">
      <table class="table1">
